📊 Telco Customer Churn Prediction
colab notebook: https://colab.research.google.com/drive/1WxOZ_Lay7GLq8c47JO19zyv0ws5bj0SO#scrollTo=W1mvqJbECgAK
🚀 Project Overview

This project develops a machine learning pipeline to predict customer churn in a telecommunications dataset. The objective is to identify customers at risk of leaving and provide actionable insights for retention strategies.

The approach emphasizes:

Structured data preprocessing
Feature engineering
Model comparison
Balanced evaluation using F1 score
🧠 Problem Statement

Customer churn directly impacts revenue and long-term growth in telecom businesses.

This project answers:

Which customers are likely to churn?
How accurately can churn be predicted?
Which model provides the best balance between precision and recall?
📁 Dataset
Source: Kaggle
Dataset: Telco Customer Churn
Features include:
Customer demographics
Service subscriptions
Billing and payment methods
Tenure and usage behavior
⚙️ Methodology
1. Data Cleaning
Removed irrelevant identifier (customerID)
Converted TotalCharges to numeric (handled coercion errors)
Imputed missing values using mean substitution
Removed duplicate records
2. Feature Engineering
Created a tenure segmentation feature (new_tenure):
new_customer (0–5 months)
regular_customer (6–35 months)
loyal_customer (36+ months)

This improves behavioral grouping and model interpretability.

3. Feature Preparation
Separated categorical and numerical features
Applied One-Hot Encoding to categorical variables
Combined encoded categorical features with numerical features
4. Target Variable
Encoded churn as binary:
Yes → 1
No → 0
5. Data Splitting Strategy
Used train-test split with stratification to preserve class distribution
Applied Stratified K-Fold awareness to reduce bias in class imbalance scenarios
6. Model Pipeline

A Scikit-learn Pipeline was used for Logistic Regression:

StandardScaler → feature normalization
LogisticRegression (class_weight='balanced') → handles class imbalance
7. Models Trained
Logistic Regression (baseline + balanced)
Decision Tree Classifier
Random Forest Classifier
📊 Model Performance
🎯 F1 Score Comparison
Model	F1 Score	Business Interpretation
Logistic Regression	0.624 (~62%)	Correctly predicts churn behavior in ~6 out of 10 customers
Random Forest	0.537 (~54%)	Moderate performance but misses a significant number of churners
Decision Tree	0.488 (~49%)	Weak generalization and inconsistent predictions
🧠 Performance Analysis
🥇 Logistic Regression (Best Model)
Achieved the highest F1 score
Strong recall (~77%), meaning most churners are detected
Balanced trade-off between false positives and false negatives
🌲 Random Forest
Highest accuracy (~78%)
Lower recall (~47%) → fails to identify many churners
Better precision, but weaker in capturing churn risk
🌳 Decision Tree
Lowest F1 score
Poor balance between precision and recall
Likely overfitting to training data
💼 Business Interpretation
⭐ Key Insight:

The best model (Logistic Regression) correctly identifies churn behavior in approximately 6 out of every 10 customers.

What this means:
Enables targeted retention campaigns
Reduces random customer outreach
Helps prioritize high-risk customers
Trade-off:
Some churners are still missed
Some non-churners may be incorrectly flagged
🔍 Key Observations
Customer tenure strongly influences churn
Contract type significantly impacts retention
Billing methods correlate with churn likelihood
⚠️ Limitations
No hyperparameter tuning applied
Cross-validation not fully utilized for performance averaging
Threshold optimization not finalized
Feature importance analysis not included
🔮 Future Improvements
Apply GridSearchCV for hyperparameter tuning
Optimize classification threshold for better F1 score
Experiment with advanced models:
Gradient Boosting
XGBoost / LightGBM
Perform feature importance analysis
Deploy model via web application (Flask / Streamlit)
🛠️ Tech Stack
Python
Pandas, NumPy
Matplotlib, Seaborn
Scikit-learn
📌 Conclusion

This project demonstrates a structured approach to solving a real-world classification problem using machine learning.

While the current best model achieves an F1 score of ~62%, it already provides meaningful predictive capability. With further optimization, the system can evolve into a reliable decision-support tool for customer retention strategies.
